Windows Explorer (the one in Win8.1, at least) won&#x27;t allow creation of files with a space at the beginning or end of a name, but it&#x27;s definitely allowed in the filesystem. For example, from a command prompt, this works:<p><pre><code>  echo hi > &quot; hello.txt&quot;
</code></pre>
Explorer can see this file and perform operations on it, but if you try to rename it to a name with leading or trailing spaces, they get trimmed.<p>I have used &#x27;~&#x27; to cause files to sort at the top - this seems to be some oddity of the sorting order that Explorer uses, since ~ would sort at the end in ASCIIbetical order - but at least it&#x27;s an allowed character at the beginning of a name in Explorer, unlike space.
